  "text": "The Kafka Streams core architecture is defined by three key classes in the apache/kafka repository (mirrored as sg-evals/kafka--0753c489):\n\n1. **Topology** (streams/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/streams/Topology.java, line 60): This public class represents a logical DAG (directed acyclic graph) of processing nodes consisting of sources, processors, and sinks. It provides methods to construct the graph by adding sources, processors, and sinks, and is the low-level representation that can be passed directly to KafkaStreams for execution.\n\n2. **StreamsBuilder** (streams/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/streams/StreamsBuilder.java, line 65): This public class provides the high-level Kafka Streams DSL (Domain-Specific Language) for building stream processing topologies. It wraps an internal Topology instance and provides convenient builder methods for defining stream transformations, allowing developers to express their processing logic in a more intuitive way.\n\n3. **KafkaStreams** (streams/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/streams/KafkaStreams.java, line 161): This public class is the runtime container that executes a topology. It implements AutoCloseable and manages the lifecycle of stream processing, including starting/stopping the application, handling consumer/producer clients, managing stream threads, and providing query interfaces for interactive queries on state stores."
}

